`FsAdapter` performs two sequential checks inside its private `resolve()` method:

## Check 1: String-based path check

```ts
const absolute = path.resolve(this.root, rel);
if (!absolute.startsWith(this.root + path.sep) && absolute !== this.root) {
  throw new Error(`Path traversal detected: ${rel}`);
}
```

After resolving the relative path against the root using `path.resolve()`, it verifies the resulting absolute path either starts with `this.root + path.sep` (i.e., is inside the root directory) or equals `this.root` exactly. This catches simple `../`-style traversal attempts like `../../etc/passwd` before any filesystem access occurs.

## Check 2: Symlink-aware realpath check

```ts
const real = await fs.promises.realpath(absolute).catch(() => absolute);
if (!real.startsWith(this.realRoot + path.sep) && real !== this.realRoot) {
  throw new Error(`Path traversal detected: ${rel}`);
}
```

After the string check passes, it dereferences all symlinks via `fs.promises.realpath()` and re-validates the resolved path against `this.realRoot` (itself computed with `fs.realpathSync.native()` at construction time). This catches symlinks inside the tree that point outside it — for example, a symlink `lib -> /etc` would pass the first string check but fail this second one. If `realpath` itself fails (e.g., the path doesn't exist yet), it falls back to the unresolved `absolute` path.

Both checks use the same boundary condition: the real path must either start with the root followed by the OS path separator, or be exactly equal to the root itself. The separator is included explicitly to prevent a root of `/foo` from incorrectly permitting `/foobar`.
